bf.t: Hi everyone. My name is Mathias and I’m here to tell you what’s new in Puppeteer!

bg.t: But before we can do that, we should probably talk about what Puppeteer is in

bh.t: the first place. Puppeteer is a browser automation library for Node.js. It lets you

bi.t: control a browser using a simple and modern JavaScript API. After installing

bj.t: it using `npm install puppeteer` you can `require('puppeteer')` in your Node.js script

bk.t: and start automating. The first step to browser automation is… to launch an

bl.t: actual browser and with Puppeteer, that’s just one line of code. Next, we open a new

bm.t: page. This is equivalent to opening a new tab in your browser. Now let’s navigate

bn.t: to a URL. This line of code ensures that the page has finished loading before

bo.t: continuing with the rest of the script. Then we take a screenshot and save it to

bp.t: a file before finally closing the browser. And that’s it — that’s the entire

bq.t: script! We did all of that with just a few lines of code. And Puppeteer can do

br.t: much more: you can generate PDFs, evaluate JavaScript in pages, enter text in input

bs.t: fields, click on elements… Almost anything you would manually do when using a

bt.t: browser can be automated using Puppeteer. The Puppeteer project is fully open source

bu.t: and has received contributions from individual contributors all around the

bv.t: world as well as from companies like Mozilla, Sauce Labs, and Microsoft. At

bw.t: Google, the Puppeteer team consists of Chrome engineers who also work on DevTools.

bx.t: This might sound a little strange at first, but it actually makes

by.t: sense, because Puppeteer is built on top of the same underlying protocol that DevTools

bz.t: also uses to communicate with the Chromium back-end. Because of this,

c0.t: Puppeteer also gives you access to advanced browser functionality that is

c1.t: usually only available through DevTools. For example, you might know that DevTools

c2.t: lets you emulate print media so that you can easily debug print styles.

c3.t: Well, Puppeteer lets you do the same thing in an automated script. Here we

c4.t: call `page.emulateMediaType` to force print styles and then we save the result

c5.t: as a PDF. Okay, now that you know what Puppeteer is, what it can do, and who is

c6.t: working on it, let’s take a look at some recent feature additions. Similar to

c7.t: emulating print styles, we recently added DevTools support for emulating light and

c8.t: dark mode as well as other so-called “CSS media features”. We then shipped a new

c9.t: Puppeteer API that lets you perform the same emulation programmatically. This

ca.t: Puppeteer script takes two screenshots of your web app: one in light mode, and

cb.t: one in dark mode. It works independently of your operating system settings. One of

cg.t: the website just tells me what I need to know in my local time. Nobody likes doing

ch.t: timezone math! To make it easier to test this kind of timezone-aware

ci.t: functionality, we added DevTools support for emulating arbitrary time zones.

cs.t: DevTools recently gained support for simulating the effect of various vision
